{
    "publish_date": "2013-03-11T11:16:27.000Z", 
    "video_length": "PT3M14S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "[MUSIC PLAYING]", 
            "dur": "10.09", 
            "start": "1.92"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "My goal is to not actually\ndo any measurements", 
            "dur": "2.98", 
            "start": "12.01"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "other than using pie.", 
            "dur": "1.47", 
            "start": "14.99"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So the entire thing is\ngoing to pie based.", 
            "dur": "4.1", 
            "start": "16.46"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "We get the circumference in\nthe exact number of pies--", 
            "dur": "3.46", 
            "start": "20.56"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "give or take-- we get the\ndiameter in number of pies.", 
            "dur": "2.75", 
            "start": "24.02"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Divide one by the other,\nwe get pi.", 
            "dur": "2.58", 
            "start": "26.77"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "[MUSIC PLAYING]", 
            "dur": "4.68", 
            "start": "29.35"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Pi was historically rarely\ncalculated this way, because", 
            "dur": "4.765", 
            "start": "34.03"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it&#39;s notoriously inaccurate\nto try and get--", 
            "dur": "2.625", 
            "start": "38.795"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I know, we&#39;re idiots-- it&#39;s\nnotoriously inaccurate to try", 
            "dur": "3.09", 
            "start": "41.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and calculate pi by measuring\na circle.", 
            "dur": "3.13", 
            "start": "44.51"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "[MUSIC PLAYING]", 
            "dur": "22.38", 
            "start": "47.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "To get any kind of accuracy on\nour final answer we have to be", 
            "dur": "3.46", 
            "start": "70.02"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "as precise as we can be.", 
            "dur": "1.42", 
            "start": "73.48"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "[MUSIC PLAYING]", 
            "dur": "4.482", 
            "start": "74.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This is a mild problem, because\nI want to go from the", 
            "dur": "2.66", 
            "start": "84.86"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "very edge of the circle.", 
            "dur": "0.77", 
            "start": "87.52"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But as you can see, I&#39;ve\npositioned all the pies", 
            "dur": "2.39", 
            "start": "88.29"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "exactly on the line as if\nthey&#39;re little mini tangents.", 
            "dur": "2.82", 
            "start": "90.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So I&#39;m going to have to move\nthese two out and then I can", 
            "dur": "3.38", 
            "start": "93.5"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "start doing the diameter exactly\non the circumference", 
            "dur": "4.04", 
            "start": "96.88"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "there, like that.", 
            "dur": "0.984", 
            "start": "100.92"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "[MUSIC PLAYING]", 
            "dur": "17.716", 
            "start": "101.904"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So that&#39;s 84 and 1/3.", 
            "dur": "3.575", 
            "start": "119.62"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "264 and 2/3 pies around,\nwe have the diameter,", 
            "dur": "4.825", 
            "start": "123.195"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is 84 and 1/3 pie.", 
            "dur": "1.84", 
            "start": "128.02"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "To get pi, we just divide the\ncircumference by the diameter.", 
            "dur": "4.26", 
            "start": "129.86"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "OK, and if we actually work out\nwhat that is, it equals--", 
            "dur": "3.135", 
            "start": "134.12"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that&#39;s pretty good.", 
            "dur": "1.264", 
            "start": "140.376"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Pi from pies, we got 3.13834,\nwhich is approximately 3.14.", 
            "dur": "12.36", 
            "start": "141.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So using pies, we&#39;ve\ngot pi to be 3.14.", 
            "dur": "6.295", 
            "start": "154"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I am a very happy\nman right now.", 
            "dur": "4.011", 
            "start": "160.295"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "With the diameter, and if I know\nthat ratio, I can just", 
            "dur": "3.764", 
            "start": "164.306"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "measure the diameter.", 
            "dur": "1.13", 
            "start": "168.07"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That&#39;s the easy bit\nto measure.", 
            "dur": "1.96", 
            "start": "169.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The center point will\nbe my pen, and the", 
            "dur": "2.84", 
            "start": "171.16"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "outside will be the chalk.", 
            "dur": "2.39", 
            "start": "174"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So the pies, in theory, are\na fairly consistent size.", 
            "dur": "4.12", 
            "start": "176.39"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So they&#39;re all--", 
            "dur": "1.17", 
            "start": "180.51"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "yeah they&#39;re about the same.", 
            "dur": "1.622", 
            "start": "181.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "OK.", 
            "dur": "0.452", 
            "start": "183.302"
        }, 
        {
